The Scottish Parliament is the second devolved parliament in the United Kingdom, following the Welsh Assembly (not to be confused with the Assembly of the United Kingdom). The Scottish Parliament is within the United Kingdom's Parliament, but is not a member of it. The Scottish Parliament was created, and continues to be created, in accordance with the Scottish Parliament Act 1998, which provides for a fixed period of ten years. In the event of a general election, the Scottish Parliament would be dissolved, and the Scottish Parliament would be placed in the hands of an election commission.

The Scottish Parliament has the power to:

authorise the appointment of High Court judges from Scotland;

authorise the appointment of National Court judges, including the President of the Court of Session;

authorise the appointment of Scottish judges to the European Court of Justice;

